	<div class="row justify-content-center">
		<div class="col-md-8 col-sm-12 justify-content-center">
			<p class="to-fill">Tanuki No Tama is a multiplayer party game in which players dashes across the screen to defend the Tanuki against waves of demons.</p>
			<p class="to-fill">It is a student projet on which I worked during my DESS at Montreal University (UdeM). We were a team of 4 and I worked on the project for 6 months as a gameplay programer and game designer. I had never been the core programmer on a project prior to Tanuki No Tama and it was an interesting challenge for me.</p>
			<p class="to-fill">Our minimal goal was to have a playable prototype and from there try and push it as close as possible to a marketable game. We ended the 6 months with a polishable game but enjoyable nonetheless. We were able to get all the core feature we wanted but still had room to enrich them (add more power ups for example). We were also happy with the look and feel thanks to our technical designer who was able to juice up the game and make it flashier and more satisfying.</p>
		</div>
	</div>
	
	<!--MY TASKS-->
	<div class="row justify-content-center">
		<div class="col-4 align-self-center divider"></div>
		<div class="col-md-2 col-sm-12">
			<h2 class="to-fill">My Tasks</h2>
		</div>
		<div class="col-4 align-self-center divider"></div>
	</div>
	
	<div class="row justify-content-center">
		<div class="col-md-8 col-sm-12">
			<h3 class="to-fill">Gameplay Programmer</h3>
			<p class="to-fill">I had a central role in the team as the gameplay programmer, I was in charge of creating the core features and the tools that allowed the rest of the team to try and tweak those.</p>
			<p class="to-fill">I worked on Unity and used C# for my scripts. I also used the library iTween to draw and easily managed enemies paths.</p>
			<p class="to-fill">We had an iteration based approach which meant that I had made my code as clean and modular as possible to be able to modify it easily. For example, our main feature went from a simple walk and dash to a walk, lock and dash to a simple lock and dash. We did several tries for each steps but having this appoach in mind, we were able to iterate quickly and not be too slowed by the programming side.</p>
		</div>
		
