	<!--WHAT I LEARNED-->
	<div class="row justify-content-center">
		<div class="col-3 align-self-center divider"></div>
		<div class="col-md-4 col-sm-12">
			<h2 class="to-fill">What I learned</h2>
		</div>
		<div class="col-3 align-self-center divider"></div>
	</div>
	
	<div class="row justify-content-center">
		<div class="col-md-5 col-sm-12">
			<img height="256px" width="100%" src="/images/TANUKI_370-256.png">
		</div>
		<div class="col-md-7 col-sm-12">
			<p class="to-fill">To help us manage our tasks and time we used a SCRUM approach. Every day we met to keep every one up to date of each other’s tasks and problems. We kept tracks of ongoing and upcoming tasks with Trello (with the extension « SCRUM for Trello »). I took a liking in this method as it is easy to set up and less stressful than a more linear method.</p>    
			<p class="to-fill">This project helped shape my current design approach. Prior to Tanuki No Tama I spent a lot of time planning and thinking about a feature instead of prototyping it and have a concrete base to work on. I was afraid to lose time developing it and wanted to anticipate and plan every detail beforehand. But I ended up still having to spend time tweaking and modifying my feature after developing it. Now I still spend time planing but I try to start prototyping as soon as I have enough material to work with and iterate from there.</p>
		</div>
	</div>
	
	<!--WHAT I WOULD DO DIFFERENTLY-->
	<div class="row justify-content-center">
